definition.value: Accessories worn on the hand.
Any element of clothing which is worn on one's head.
Various styles of clothing worn around the (human) neck.
Clothing, as sorted by particular events or occasions.
Clothing designed to be worn while sleeping.
Items of clothing designed to be worn by people engaging in a water-based activity or water sports, such as swimming, diving and surfing, or sun-orientated activities, such as sun bathing.
An item used to contribute, in a secondary manner, to the wearer's outfit, often used to complete an outfit and chosen to specifically complement the wearer's look.
Clothing accessories that are primarily carried.
Clothing accessories that are primarily worn.
Clothing sorted by typically wearer's gender identity, expression, and/or role in a given societal context.
Clothing sorted by typically wearer's male gender identity, expression, and/or role in a given societal context.
Clothing sorted by typically wearer's female gender identity, expression, and/or role in a given societal context.
Clothing, as sorted by the age group of the wearer.
Clothing designed for use by children.
Clothing primarily utilized by adults.
Clothing for infants.
Accessories worn on the arm.
Any device worn over the eyes.
Clothing, as sorted by primary material or materials.
Clothing made of leather.
Clothing made of latex.
Clothing made of rubber.
Clothing made of the plastic polyvinyl chloride (PVC).
A small bag for the purpose of carrying currency, usually coins.

The term "purse" originally referred to a small bag for holding coins. In many English-speaking countries it is still used to refer to a small money bag. A "handbag" is a larger accessory that holds objects beyond currency, such as personal items. American English typically uses the terms purse and handbag interchangeably.
A handled medium-to-large bag used to carry personal items.

The term "purse" originally referred to a small bag for holding coins. In many English-speaking countries it is still used to refer to a small money bag. A "handbag" is a larger accessory that holds objects beyond currency, such as personal items. American English typically uses the terms purse and handbag interchangeably.

A bag, often with a strap. The strap is often worn so that it diagonally crosses the body, with the bag hanging on the opposite hip, rather than hanging directly down from the shoulder. They are traditionally used for carrying books. The back of a satchel extends to form a flap that folds over to cover the top and fastens in the front. Unlike a briefcase, a satchel is soft-sided.
A narrow hard-sided box-shaped bag or case used mainly for carrying papers and equipped with a handle.
Cloth-covered frame used for protection against rain.
A small light umbrella used as protection from the sun.

A device used primarily to aid walking, provide postural stability or support, or assist in maintaining a good posture, but some designs also serve as a fashion accessory, or are used for self-defense.
Footwear made of a flat sole shaped to the contour of the foot, connected to an upper portion which may or may not completely cover or wrap around the foot.
Small decorative items worn for personal adornment, such as brooches, rings, necklaces, earrings, pendants, bracelets, and cufflinks. Jewelry may be attached to the body or the clothes.
Jewelry worn in one's hair.
Jewelry worn in and/or around one's nose.
Jewelry worn on one's hand or hands (or one's wrist or wrists).
Jewelry worn around one's neck.
Jewelry worn around one's arm.
Jewelry worn around one's finger or fingers.
Jewelry worn upon one's head.
An article of jewelry that is worn around the neck, most often made of a string of precious metal, pearls, gems, beads or shells, and sometimes having a pendant attached.

A close-fitting necklace worn around the neck. Chokers can be made of a variety of materials, including velvet, plastic, beads, latex, leather, metal, such as silver, gold or platinum, etc. They can be adorned in a variety of ways, including with sequins, studs, or a pendant.
A necklace 35 centimetres (14 in) to 41 centimetres (16 in) long that sits high on the neck.
A princess necklace is 45 centimetres (18 in) to 50 centimetres (20 in) long, longer than a choker, but shorter than a matinee.
A matinee length necklace is 56 centimetres (22 in) to 58 centimetres (23 in) long  typically a single strand that rests at the top of the cleavage.
An opera necklace is 75 centimetres (30 in) to 90 centimetres (35 in) long and sits at the breastbone.
A rope necklace is any necklace longer than opera length.

A lariat is a very, very long variation on the rope, without a clasp, often worn draped multiple times around the neck; the ends can be crossed over, looped, or knotted in various ways. This type of necklace sometimes incorporates a loop at one or both ends to allow it to be worn in the style of a lasso, or it may be worn doubled over with the ends passed through the loop formed in the middle.
A long piece of cloth, worn, usually by men, for decorative purposes around the neck, resting under the shirt collar and knotted at the throat.
A circular band worn as a type of ornamental jewelry around the finger.

A ring indicating that the person wearing it is engaged to be married. A ring is presented as an engagement gift by a partner to their prospective spouse when they propose marriage or directly after a marriage proposal is accepted. It represents a formal agreement to future marriage.
A finger ring that indicates that its wearer is married. It is usually forged from metal, and traditionally is forged of gold or another precious metal.
